d:list.d:item:
@level is only used in the context of a bibliography entry; it is used to
differentiate a monograph title from the title of a multi-authored book in which the
work being described appears, for example.

@xml:id: when names of project members are given in respStmt
elements in corpus.xml, they are assigned unique IDs via this attribute there. These IDS
can be used to reference them elsewhere, usually using @resp.

d:desc.d:p:
Used within publicationStmt in a transcription file header, this provides a
         publication ID for the transcription. This should be the same as the value of the
            @xml:id attribute of the ancestor TEI.

d:list.d:item:
@min and @max are used to give a much broader estimate of the
period in which the scribe was active and may be the only dating attributes used if not
positive information about the scribe is available.

@type indicates what sort of span @from and @to /
   @min and @max relate to. Possible values include "floruit" and
"lifespan".

d:desc.d:p:
This element contains a number or range, which is the number of pages, volumes, etc.
         taken up by the bibliography item. The unit involved is indicated via
         @unit.

This element is used within editorial commentary (in teiHeader or in
         footnotes) to specify how a string of text is to be formatted in the output. This is done
         using @rend, which can use values like:

This element is contained by taxonomy and details an ID or attribute/element
         value in use across the corpus. The ID or attribute/element value is identified via
            @xml:id and the definition contained as text within gloss.

The abbreviation or ligature is assigned a unique ID via @xml:id;
         abbreviations' IDs are prefixed "g" and ligatures' IDs are prefixed "l". If it appears in
         the Tionscadal na
            Nod database, then a URL for its entry there is provided via
         @corresp.

In the teiHeader of a transcription file, these handNote elements
         are empty and merely point to the handNote elements in copus.xml via
            @corresp, which has as a value the scribe's unique ID.

d:list.d:item:
@n: this is the number assigned to the text/subdivision; it is not a
unique ID but will display on screen to indicate where the text is in the transcription
in certain sorts of output.

@type: this identifies whether the text is "prose", "verse", or
"divprose" (subdivided prose); if it is a subdivision of prose text, the value will be
"prosediv".

@hand: this identifies the main scribe responsible for the text; if
multiple scribes are involved, it identifies the first major scribal
contributor.

@n: This is the number of the new page, based on the conventional
foliation of the manuscript; it need not be a unique ID but it will appear to designate
the new page in some outputs.

@facs: This provides a URL for an online image of the new page, where
available; it must be a link directly to the image, not to a page that contains the
image.

@sameAs: Where the new page begins in the middle of a word that requires
editorial emendation, the pb element must be provided twice; as it cannot be
given two @xml:id attributes with the same value, as there can only be one
   @xml:id with a given value in a document, @sameAs must be used
in any other instances of the pb.

@sameAs: Where the new line begins in the middle of a word that requires
editorial emendation, the lb element must be provided twice; as it cannot be
given two @xml:id attributes with the same value, as there can only be one
   @xml:id with a given value in a document, @sameAs must be used
in any other instances of the lb.

@lemma: this indicates the headword of which the transcribed word has
been identified as a form. If the word cannot be identified with a headword in the form
in which it appears, the value of @lemma is "UNKNOWN".

@source: if the headword has been postulated based on another headword,
the postulated headword is provided via @lemma (prefixed with *) and the
nearest identified headword provided via @source; the URL for the
   @source headword is provided via @lemmaRef.

@xml:lang: if the word is not in some form of Gaelic, the language is
specified via this attribute using its XML language code. In such cases, no attributes
other than @id (see below).

@force: this will create a space in the "Semi-Diplomatic" edition on
Meanma where a space would not otherwise be added according to the standard rules that
Meanma applies.

d:desc.d:p:
The certainty with which the transcriber has provided the text in unclear is
         indicated via @cert. The transcriber responsible is identified via
            @resp.

d:list.d:item:
@quantity: the length of the gap in the specified unit (e.g. "3", where
   @unit="chars", to indicate that the gap allows space for three
characters).

d:desc.d:p:
In all instances, the editor responsible for attempting to estimate the gap is indicated
         via @resp using their unique ID. Furthermore, c requires a unique
            @id in order to be compliant with the DASG schema.
